# Localization and RTL Rules

## Bilingual Requirement

- Admin UI MUST support English and Hebrew — do NOT ship English-only components
- Every user-facing string in every admin component must use a translation key — no hardcoded strings in JSX or component logic
- Locale files live at:
  - `apps/admin/locales/en/common.json`
  - `apps/admin/locales/he/common.json`
- Every key added to one locale file must be added to the other in the same commit — partial keys are not acceptable
- Missing keys fall back to English, but this fallback is a warning state, not an acceptable ship state

## RTL Structural Requirements

- Hebrew locale MUST set `dir="rtl"` on the `<html>` element — do NOT set it only on inner containers
- All layout components must use Tailwind RTL utility classes:
  - `rtl:text-right` instead of hardcoded `text-right`
  - `rtl:flex-row-reverse` instead of hardcoded `flex-row-reverse`
  - `rtl:mr-0 rtl:ml-auto` to mirror margin logic
  - `rtl:space-x-reverse` where horizontal spacing is used in flex rows
- Never use absolute or fixed positioning for navigation or layout elements that would break in RTL — use logical CSS properties or Tailwind RTL variants
- If a component uses `left-*` or `right-*` Tailwind classes for layout, it must also declare the RTL mirror using `rtl:left-*` / `rtl:right-*`

## Component-Level Localization Rules

- Score breakdown tables must render column order and text alignment correctly in both LTR and RTL
- Modals and drawers must open from the correct edge in RTL — use `end` positioning, not `start` or `left`
- Form labels, placeholders, validation messages, and ARIA labels must all be translated — not just visible text
- Empty state messages, loading indicators, and error banners must have translated text in both locales
- Tooltips and hover text must use translation keys — they are user-facing strings

## Locale Switcher

- A locale switcher must be visible and accessible on every page of the admin UI
- The selected locale must persist across navigation — store in a cookie or localStorage, not only in component state
- Switching locale must not require a full page reload if the framework supports client-side locale switching

## Typography

- Hebrew text must use `Rubik` or `Heebo` font family — do NOT fall back to system sans-serif for Hebrew UI text
- Load the Hebrew font via the project's font configuration — do not rely on CDN at runtime in production

## Number and Date Formatting

- All numbers, dates, and currency values must be formatted using the `Intl` API with the active locale — example: `new Intl.DateTimeFormat(locale).format(date)`
- Do NOT hardcode date formats such as `MM/DD/YYYY` or `DD/MM/YYYY` — these are locale-specific
- Percentage and score values must respect locale decimal and grouping separators via `Intl.NumberFormat`

## Validation Before Shipping

- Before marking any admin UI component complete, verify:
  - Both locale files have the required keys
  - The component renders without layout breakage in RTL (manual check or snapshot)
  - No hardcoded strings remain in JSX
  - Font loads correctly for Hebrew text
